Judge Neil Gorsuch is an excellent choice to be the next Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court, and a fitting choice to fill Justice Antonin Scalia's seat. Throughout his career, Judge Gorsuch has demonstrated he is commitment to interpreting law, not using the Court to make laws.   I applaud President Donald Trump’s selection. Judge Gorsuch’s extensive credentials and impeccable qualifications should earn bipartisan support. I urge the Senate to confirm his nomination swiftly.

This was an exciting week in Congress, packed with legislation, constituent meetings, and committee hearings. House Republicans are working hand in hand with our new administration to bring positive change for hardworking American families.

“While I take inspiration from the past, like most Americans, I live for the future.” Today we honor the birthday of a true American hero and a source of inspiration for me, President Ronald Reagan. I was grateful to serve on staff with the Reagan Administration and I believe that he laid a positive foundation of limited government and expanded freedom that we can continue to build upon today.

For too long, the dictatorship in North Korea has become emboldened—testing nuclear weapons, but also testing and expanding their ballistic missile capability. Just last month, North Korea announced their plans to test an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM).    It is time to stand up to North Korea’s aggression--an ICBM with a nuclear warhead is a direct threat to the United States and our allies, especially South Korea. The resolution I introduced today is a key first step towards achieving peace through strength.

Friends,   Thank you very much for signing up for the town hall by telephone. I am grateful that you took time to sign up and planned to participate in the call.   Earlier this afternoon, I was asked to attend Congressman Mick Mulvaney’s swearing in ceremony as Director of the Office of Management and Budget. While the ceremony conflicts with our scheduled town hall, I believe it is important to stand with my colleague during this historic moment in South Carolina history. I have rescheduled the call for March 1st at 6 pm.   In the coming weeks and months, I will be calling on Director Mulvaney to support necessary efforts to rebuild our military, support the critical national security and environmental clean-up missions at the Savannah River Site and MOX facility, and to work together to rein in federal spending.   I appreciate your understanding for rescheduling the call. I will now hold the town hall by telephone on March 1, 2017, at 6 pm. The sign up link for the call will remain active in the interim, and if you signed up to be called tonight, you do not need to sign up again – your registration will transfer.   Additionally, if you have questions about issues before Congress, you can also contact the office

Families in the Second Congressional District and across the country have seen firsthand how Obamacare has failed—destroying jobs, increasing premiums, spiraling deductibles, and lack of health care choices. We need a real solution that gives everyone access to quality, affordable insurance.   I am grateful that yesterday, House Republicans introduced legislation that puts American people in charge of their health care – not the federal government. Our bill specifically protects those with pre-existing conditions, allows young adults to remain on their parent’s insurance until they are 26, and provides a stable transition to our system of lower costs and increased options.      I encourage all of my constituents to go to readthebill.gop to hear how we are simultaneously repealing and replacing Obamacare with a health care system that works.

Today marks #GoldStarSpousesDay - a day to honor the sacrifice too many military families have made.   Sadly, for too long, the Survivor Benefit Plan – Dependency and Indemnity Compensation offset has been an unfair penalty that cuts earned benefits to military survivors. Our nation’s military personnel risk their lives to defend our nation and our freedoms—they should be able to trust that the benefits they designate for their spouses and families will provide for them.   That's why I've introduced the Military Surviving Spouses Equity Act, legislation that would support military families faced with the SBP-DIC off-set. It is past time that we address this discrepancy. Families of our fallen heroes are counting on us.

I’ve heard from many constituents concerned about how the American Health Care Act (AHCA) might affect those with preexisting conditions. Here are the facts:    Under the AHCA, no one can be denied coverage because of a pre-existing condition. No one will be charged higher premiums if they have maintained their coverage. Those who still need help with health insurance premiums will receive tax credits to help them purchase insurance.    I encourage you to read more about the contents of this bill and learn how this bill will reduce premiums for American families and increase choices for health care.

Since the Peanut Standards Board was created in 2002, South Carolina’s peanut farmers have been without a voice in the U.S. Department of Agriculture, despite being the nation’s fourth largest peanut-producing state. This legislation would rectify an imbalance on the Peanut Standards Board and support South Carolina peanut farmers. Peanuts are so appreciated in South Carolina that the state legislature designated the boiled peanut as the state’s official snack.

Military families face unique struggles—managing frequent moves, disruptions during the school year, and lack of choice in educational opportunities. As more and more families look to homeschooling as a way to standardize education and maintain consistency in transitions, they struggle to manage the costs. This legislation would expand the use of tax-free educational savings accounts for military families for homeschooling costs, in addition to qualified public, private, or religious schools.   By promoting school choice for children of active duty service members, we can support military families and help alleviate concerns faced by military families that can have a negative impact on troop retention.

Good news! The House of Representatives passed the Financial CHOICE Act today, a huge step forward today in undoing the regulatory burdens of Dodd-Frank.  The Financial CHOICE Act presents a clear path forward for American families by holding Wall Street accountable, increasing transparency in regulatory agencies, and supporting small businesses, which creates jobs.   I am especially grateful that the CHOICE Act repeals the Fiduciary Rule, a burdensome 1,000 page regulation that increases costs and limits choices for families saving for retirement.

I am grateful that the House Foreign Affairs Committee passed H.R. 3542, the Hamas Human Shields Prevention Act today. Hamas terrorists have taken shelter among civilians and launched attacks against Israel from schools, hospitals and mosques for many years. In doing so, they have turned defenseless men, women and children into human shields. This is not only a violation of international law, it’s an atrocious abuse of human rights – and it’s past time that we stand up to Hamas. This is a crucial step towards imposing direct sanctions on Hamas terrorists who use civilians as human shields.

It’s been more than a generation since Congress passed meaningful tax reform. After months of talking about tax cuts this year, the American people wanted to see members of Congress take action. That’s exactly what Republicans have done. The ‘Tax Cuts & Jobs Act’ makes the tax code simpler and fairer, allows hardworking taxpayers to keep more of the money they earn and gives small businesses more room to grow and create jobs.  When taxes are low, businesses thrive, and jobs are created in the Reagan tradition. I am grateful for the leadership of Speaker Ryan and House Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady, and I look forward to working with them, in addition to President Donald Trump, on delivering meaningful tax relief to the American people. They deserve it.

This was a big week on Capitol Hill with the House passage of the FY18 National Defense Authorization Act - one of the most important bills of the year. I was grateful that the House Foreign Affairs Committee passed a bipartisan bill I introduced to sanction Hamas terrorists when they use civilians as human shields. I was humbled to host a breakfast roundtable discussion with former U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations, John Bolton, and colleagues including Congressman Steve Scalise. Additionally, this week House Republicans passed a tax cuts bill that makes the tax code simpler and fairer, allows hardworking taxpayers to keep more of the money they earn, and gives small businesses more room to grow and create jobs. Check out This Week With Wilson to learn more - and SHARE with family and friends!

North Korea’s latest nuclear missile test was its most provocative to date, putting all American families at risk, and it’s more important than ever that North Korea’s neighbors take the reckless regime’s continual escalation of nuclear threats as seriously as we do. Ambassador Nikki Haley was absolutely right when she urged China – and its President Xi Jingping – to do more to stop North Korea from pushing the world closer to nuclear war. I support Ambassador Haley and President Donald Trump’s national security team, all of whom know that peace through strength is what it takes to keep American families safe, and I join them in calling for China to cut off oil from North Korea.
